I think a lot about the millennials who were the last generation able to form connections with artists without the pressure of having a critical eye.
We arrived during a golden age of media, with a collective awareness of pop culture that no longer exists.
We plunged directly into things without worrying about the source, because it wasn't so easy to determine.
without questioning the pedestal on which they placed us, parasocial relationships had become foundations for our lives.
That's why we are so attached to nostalgia.
When The Office was still on, my friends and I would order pizzas and watch the show every Thursday.
It resembled nothing like what we have now with streaming, where 12 episodes are suddenly available and everyone watches at their own pace, starting social media posts with "spoiler alert" or continuing in specific closed spaces.
unconsciously we yearn to reconnect with the universal community that surrounded all of this
That's why so many of us watch series like The Office or movies like Anchorman, with lots of short references, just like memes.
we repeated these refs, knowing that most people knew them
now, even when something becomes completely viral, we can't know if everyone has seen it.
there are too many things to see and no way to rationalize them all... will we escape hyper-saturation?
we get caught in cycles of discovering new media, only to realize that the artist is a predator or a fanatic.
We are forced to deal with a situation where we cling to nostalgia while acknowledging that the people who created the art we connect with can be very imperfect.
we delve into parasocial relationships by paying more attention.
we realize that it's hard to reach these positions of wealth and power without trampling on others along the way.
without collective awareness of the media, we developed a class consciousness that helps us remain critical.
some of us continue to put people on a pedestal, only to be shocked when they fall.
we are in a tumultuous period and I can't wait to see where it will lead us.
